Evaluating performance of benchmarked spatial transcriptomic methods on the DLPFC dataset

Sam Reynoso

February 22, 2024

Introduction

To directly evaluate the information derived in the low-dimensional embeddings learned from different methods, we assess the performance of how the identified low-dimensional embeddings from STew and other methods could predict ground truth manual labels.

We tested this pipeline using the 10X Genomics Visium dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) spatial transcriptomic data. Manual annotation labels are available as ground truth.

Initialize a data frame to store results

results_df <- data.frame(Method = character(),
                         ComponentCount = integer(),
                         AdjustedPseudoR2 = numeric(),
                         AdjustedPseudoR2_CI_Lower = numeric(),
                         AdjustedPseudoR2_CI_Upper = numeric(),
                         Accuracy = numeric(),
                         CI_Lower = numeric(),
                         CI_Upper = numeric(),
                         MeanSensitivity = numeric(),
                         Sensitivity_CI_Lower = numeric(),
                         Sensitivity_CI_Upper = numeric(),
                         MeanSpecificity = numeric(),
                         Specificity_CI_Lower = numeric(),
                         Specificity_CI_Upper = numeric(),
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE)


DLPFC_methods <- c("STew", "stLearn", "SpaceFlow", "PCA")
component_counts <- c(4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14)
set.seed(123)

Load the data and perform the analysis

please make sure your files of each method are in the same folder. the files should be in the same format as the example below: ’“DLPFC_”, method, “_components_sub.rds”’

for(component_count in component_counts) {
  for(method in DLPFC_methods) {
    file_path <- paste0("/Users/milligan-mcclellanlab/Desktop/Components_pseudo-R2_benchmarking/DLPFC_", method, "_components_sub.rds")
    DLPFC_data <- readRDS(file_path)
    
    if (method == "stLearn") {
      rownames(DLPFC_data) <- DLPFC_data[,1]
      DLPFC_data <- DLPFC_data[,-1]
    }
    
    annotations <- unlist(readRDS("/Users/milligan-mcclellanlab/Desktop/Components_pseudo-R2_benchmarking/Manual_annotation_3639cells.rds"))
    
    # Split the data into training and test, p = .7 is the percentage of the data used for training
    trainIndex <- createDataPartition(annotations, p = .7, list = FALSE)
    
    # If the number of components is greater than the number of columns in the data, use the number of columns
    num_columns <- min(ncol(DLPFC_data), component_count)
    if (num_columns > 0) {
      train_data <- DLPFC_data[trainIndex, 1:num_columns] # Select the first num_columns columns
      test_data <- DLPFC_data[-trainIndex, 1:num_columns] 
      annotations_train <- annotations[trainIndex] # Select the training annotations
      annotations_test <- annotations[-trainIndex] # Select the test annotations
      
      # Fit multinomial logistic regression model
      model <- multinom(annotations_train ~ ., data = train_data)
      null_model <- multinom(annotations_train ~ 1, data = train_data)
      
      k <- model$rank - 1 # Number of predictors excluding intercept
      logLik_full <- -model$deviance / 2
      logLik_null <- -null_model$deviance / 2
      
      # Calculate McFadden's Adjusted Pseudo R2
      adjustedPseudoR2 <- 1 - ((logLik_full - k) / logLik_null)
      
      # Bootstrap for Adjusted Pseudo R2 Confidence Intervals
      bootstrap_iterations <- 100  # Use a smaller number for quicker computation
      adjustedPseudoR2_samples <- numeric(bootstrap_iterations)
      
      # Bootstrap for Adjusted Pseudo R2 Confidence Intervals
      for (i in 1:bootstrap_iterations) {
        bootstrap_indices <- sample(1:nrow(train_data), replace = TRUE) # Sample with replacement
        bootstrap_train_data <- train_data[bootstrap_indices, ] # Use the bootstrap indices to select rows
        bootstrap_annotations_train <- annotations_train[bootstrap_indices] # Use the bootstrap indices to select annotations
        
        bootstrap_model <- multinom(bootstrap_annotations_train ~ ., data = bootstrap_train_data) # Fit the model
        bootstrap_null_model <- multinom(bootstrap_annotations_train ~ 1, data = bootstrap_train_data) # Fit the null model
        
        k <- bootstrap_model$rank - 1 # Number of predictors excluding intercept
        logLik_full <- -bootstrap_model$deviance / 2 
        logLik_null <- -bootstrap_null_model$deviance / 2 
        bootstrap_adjustedPseudoR2 <- 1 - ((logLik_full - k) / logLik_null) # Calculate Adjusted Pseudo R2
        
        adjustedPseudoR2_samples[i] <- bootstrap_adjustedPseudoR2 # Store the result
      }
      # Calculate the confidence interval for Adjusted Pseudo R2 using 95% CI
      adjustedPseudoR2_CI <- quantile(adjustedPseudoR2_samples, probs = c(0.025, 0.975)) 
      
      # Predicting and calculating accuracy
      predictions_train <- predict(model, newdata = train_data, "class")
      predictions_test <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, "class")
      
      # Building classification tables for accuracy calculation
      tab_train <- table(annotations_train, predictions_train)
      tab_test <- table(annotations_test, predictions_test)
      
      # Initialize vectors to store sensitivity and specificity for each class
    sensitivity_per_class <- numeric(length = nrow(tab_test))
    specificity_per_class <- numeric(length = nrow(tab_test))
    
    for (i in 1:nrow(tab_test)) {
      # True Positives (TP)
      TP <- tab_test[i, i]
      # False Negatives (FN) for class i
      FN <- sum(tab_test[i, ]) - TP
      # False Positives (FP) for class i
      FP <- sum(tab_test[, i]) - TP
      # True Negatives (TN) for class i
      TN <- sum(tab_test) - TP - FP - FN
      
      # Calculate sensitivity and specificity for class i
      sensitivity_per_class[i] <- TP / (TP + FN)
      specificity_per_class[i] <- TN / (TN + FP)
    }
    
      # Calculate mean sensitivity and specificity across all classes
      mean_sensitivity <- mean(sensitivity_per_class)
      mean_specificity <- mean(specificity_per_class)
      
      bootstrap_mean_sensitivities <- numeric(bootstrap_iterations) 
      bootstrap_mean_specificities <- numeric(bootstrap_iterations)

    for (i in 1:bootstrap_iterations) {
      bootstrap_indices <- sample(1:nrow(test_data), replace = TRUE)
      bootstrap_test_data <- test_data[bootstrap_indices, ]
      bootstrap_annotations_test <- annotations_test[bootstrap_indices]
      
      # Recalculate predictions using the original model (no need to refit it)
      predictions_bootstrap <- predict(model, newdata = bootstrap_test_data, "class")
      
      # Recalculate the confusion matrix
      tab_bootstrap <- table(bootstrap_annotations_test, predictions_bootstrap)
      
      # Recalculate sensitivities for this bootstrap sample
      bootstrap_sensitivity_per_class <- numeric(length = nrow(tab_bootstrap)) #
      bootstrap_specificity_per_class <- numeric(length = nrow(tab_bootstrap))

     # Calculate sensitivity and specificity for each class 
    for (j in 1:nrow(tab_bootstrap)) {
      TP <- tab_bootstrap[j, j]
      FN <- sum(tab_bootstrap[j, ]) - TP
      FP <- sum(tab_bootstrap[, j]) - TP
      TN <- sum(tab_bootstrap) - TP - FP - FN
      bootstrap_sensitivity_per_class[j] <- TP / (TP + FN)
      bootstrap_specificity_per_class[j] <- TN / (TN + FP)
  }
  
  # Calculate and store the mean sensitivity for this bootstrap sample
  bootstrap_mean_sensitivities[i] <- mean(bootstrap_sensitivity_per_class, na.rm = TRUE)
  bootstrap_mean_specificities[i] <- mean(bootstrap_specificity_per_class, na.rm = TRUE)

}

# Calculate the confidence interval for mean sensitivity
sensitivity_CI <- quantile(bootstrap_mean_sensitivities, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))
specificity_CI <- quantile(bootstrap_mean_specificities, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))

    
      # Calculating accuracy for both train and test
      accuracy_train <- sum(diag(tab_train)) / sum(tab_train)
      accuracy_test <- sum(diag(tab_test)) / sum(tab_test)
      
      accuracy <- round(accuracy_test * 100, 2) # Using test accuracy for example
      
      ci <- binom.test(x = sum(diag(tab_test)), n = sum(tab_test), conf.level = 0.95)
      
      # Append results to the DataFrame
      results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(Method = method,
                                           ComponentCount = component_count,
                                           AdjustedPseudoR2 = adjustedPseudoR2,
                                           AdjustedPseudoR2_CI_Lower = adjustedPseudoR2_CI[1],
                                           AdjustedPseudoR2_CI_Upper = adjustedPseudoR2_CI[2],
                                           Accuracy = accuracy,
                                           CI_Lower = ci$conf.int[1] * 100, # Convert to percentage
                                           CI_Upper = ci$conf.int[2] * 100, # Convert to percentage
                                           MeanSensitivity = mean_sensitivity,
                                           Sensitivity_CI_Lower = sensitivity_CI[1],
                                           Sensitivity_CI_Upper = sensitivity_CI[2],
                                           MeanSpecificity = mean_specificity,
                                           Specificity_CI_Lower = specificity_CI[1],
                                           Specificity_CI_Upper = specificity_CI[2],
                                           stringsAsFactors = FALSE))
    }
  }
}

Accuracy Plot

method_colors <- c("STew" = "#a4090c", 
                   "stLearn" = "#08901a", 
                   "SpaceFlow" = "#121d96",
                   "PCA" = "#eeae00")

ggplot(results_df, aes(x = ComponentCount, y = Accuracy, group = Method, color = Method)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1.5) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = CI_Lower, ymax = CI_Upper), width = 0.2) + 
  labs(title = "",
       x = "Number of Components",
       y = "Accuracy (%)") +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 22),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 24), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 24),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 22),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 22),
        text = element_text(size = 20)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = method_colors) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(4, 14, 2))

McFadden’s Adjusted Pseudo R2 Plot
